&quot;Mika.......&quot;  She had returned, but from what.  He saw no physical wounds, but.....he could sense something.  Under all her bravado and strength had always hidden an emotional girl just looking for love, but they hid something more now.  Something more personal.  But that didn't matter.  She had returned.  A slight hint of color returned to his cheeks which had been pale for months, and the lips which hadn't parted except to speak formed a smile.  It was nothing like her big, tooty grin, but it was a smile.  He wanted to hug her, to embrace her, and never let her go.  Never to leave her, never again.  No, they had never been that close.  But she was more than just Mika to him.  She was a chance for salvation and a return to the times when he smiled more often.  He quelched the urge, and said, &quot;I've missed you&quot;, and under his breath, added, 'more than you can ever know.' <br>
<br>
OOC (Beginning to think I can't write well in an RP....Oh, btw, has anyone ever read anything by Mercedes Lackey?  Well, in her books the people can have innate abilities which I think kinda mirror those we have/had in s'just life.  <br>
Mindspeech-can talk to others, hear their thoughts, and to a degree, attack with it(mental screaming of a sort.  Only used by the strongest mind speakers)  <br>
Empaths-Can feel other's emotions, and help to change them.  Greatly helps people with emotional trauma, and can help people come over fears/heal faters/etc.  Strongest of them can attack with emotions etc fear, anger, hatred.<br>
Fetchers-Can move things.  Can move objects to and fro, the larger the object the harder to move.  The strongest can move people, even themselves, but without great strength and concentration they run the risk of jumbling up the peoples insides ergo-killing them.  Even for the best its a big risk.<br>
 <p>Ignis Summa Pugnabat, The fires shall cleanse the world.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bfantasystoriesforum.showUserPublicProfile?gid=paradisetheheretic>Paradise the Heretic</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://Auction.2y.net/user/paradisetheheretic/paradise.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mistress of Decay</span><br>  Posts: 275<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/3/03 10:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ffantasystoriesforumfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://auction.2y.net/user/paradisetheheretic/paradise.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> i love the smell of curry in the morning</span><hr size=1> &quot;Don't worry about the groceries,&quot;  Mika blurted out, still trying to keep tabs on her emotions, &quot;i brought curry,  it's over there by devin&quot;  she said as she turned and motioned in his direction.  Then she saw it.  Her old friends, in the same room together again.  She couldn't help but smile.  but in that smile she also carried longing and sorrow.  Here her friends were, those that she had not seen in far too long.  But there were still some missing.  and the one to whom her thoughts were humbled all . . . well . . . she still hadn't found her.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Mika, slightly blushed, fumbled with her cigarettes, mumbled something about going out to get some fresh air and quickly brushed by Jarron and headed down the stairs and out the door.  She needed time to t hink.  She needed time to catch up with herself.  she was beging to wonder if coming back had been such a good idea, maybe she should have stayed in central america,  . . . maybe she should have given her life instead of her soul.  <br>
<br>
she walked the lonely streets as the sun set and the wind howled.  she spoke to neferiti, quietly, under her breath, and she spoke to herself, loud enough that the few passers by gave her funny looks and crossed to the other side of the street when she got near.  she spoke to the wind and asked it for help.  she stopped dead in her tracks when, to her suprise, it answered.  ghostly childish voices came to her on the wind, tickled her ears and made the hair on the back of her neck stand on end.  the speech was incomprehencible but it maintained that certian sophistication that seperated it from the natural sounds and turned it into speech.  <br>
<br>
a single tear rolled from her eye.  she stood in the street, shiviering in the cool evening breeze, home, but not complete.<br>
<br>
